['Subsistence farming: This type of farming focuses on producing enough food to meet the needs of the farmer and their family, with any surplus often being sold or traded in local markets.', 'Commercial farming: This type of farming is focused on producing crops or livestock for sale in commercial markets, often on a large scale.', 'Organic farming: This type of farming avoids the use of synthetic fertilizers and pesticides, instead relying on natural methods to control pests and improve soil health.', 'Permaculture: This type of farming focuses on creating sustainable and self-sufficient agricultural systems, often using techniques such as polyculture and agroforestry.', 'Aquaponics: This type of farming combines aquaculture (raising fish) with hydroponics (growing plants in water) to create a closed-loop system where waste from the fish is used to fertilize the plants, and the plants help purify the water for the fish.', 'Biodynamic farming: This type of farming focuses on treating the farm as an interconnected whole, using natural preparations and astrological influences to optimize plant growth and soil health.', 'Agroforestry: This type of farming involves integrating trees into agricultural landscapes, often alongside crops or livestock, to provide shade, improve soil health, and create habitat for beneficial insects and wildlife.', 'Regenerative agriculture: This type of farming focuses on improving the health of the soil through practices such as no-till or reduced-till farming, cover cropping, and integrating livestock into the farm system.', 'Hydroponics: This type of farming involves growing plants in water rather than soil, often using nutrient-rich solutions to provide the necessary nutrients for plant growth.', 'Vertical farming: This type of farming involves growing plants in vertically stacked layers, often in indoor environments, to maximize space and improve crop yields.']
